The '''Qatar national football team''' ({{langx|ar|منتخب قطر لكرة القدم}}), nicknamed "The Maroons", represents [[Qatar]] in international [[association football|football]], and is controlled by the Qatar Football Association, which is affiliated with the [[Asian Football Confederation]] (AFC) and comes under the global jurisdiction of world football’s governing body [[FIFA]]. They play their home games at [[Jassim bin Hamad Stadium]]. The latter is considered the home stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qatarvisitor.com/world-cup-2022/qatar-stadiums|title=Qatar stadia|publisher=qatarvisitor.com|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-date=27 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227040413/http://www.qatarvisitor.com/world-cup-2022/qatar-stadiums|url-status=live}}</ref>

The team won the Arabian Gulf Cup in [[11th Arabian Gulf Cup|1992]], [[17th Arabian Gulf Cup|2004]] and [[22nd Arabian Gulf Cup|2014]]. They have appeared in ten [[AFC Asian Cup|Asian Cup]] tournaments and won it twice in [[2019 AFC Asian Cup|2019]] and [[2023 AFC Asian Cup|2023]], beating [[Japan national football team|Japan]], [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]], and [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] in the process during 2019, conceding just one goal.

Qatar hosted the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] and therefore qualified automatically for what was their first appearance in the event. Amidst the controversy, it was the first time an [[Arab world|Arab nation]] hosted the competition.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/articles/hostcountry-en | title=Host Country | date= | access-date=2022-12-28 | archive-date=29 December 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221229075022/https://www.fifa.com/fifaplus/en/articles/hostcountry-en | url-status=live }}</ref> On 25 November 2022, Qatar were the first team to be eliminated from the World Cup; subsequently, they became the worst performing host nation in the history of the FIFA World Cup, losing every game. On 14 October 2025, Qatar qualified directly for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]] after a 2–1 victory over the United Arab Emirates.<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 October 2025 |title=Qatar and Saudi Arabia qualify for 2026 World Cup |url=https://global.espn.com/football/story/_/id/46597037/qatar-saudi-arabia-qualify-2026-fifa-world-cup |access-date=15 October 2025 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref>

Qatar has footballing rivalries with [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/qatar-world-cup-bahrain-lost-economic-opportunity | title=Qatar World Cup 2022: A lost economic opportunity for Bahrain? | date=2022-11-10 | access-date=2023-01-17 | archive-date=17 January 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230117162643/https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/qatar-world-cup-bahrain-lost-economic-opportunity | url-status=live }}</ref> [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.euronews.com/culture/2022/12/07/beyond-rivalry-shared-passion-brings-football-fans-together-in-dubai | title=Beyond rivalry, shared passion brings football fans together in Dubai | date=2022-12-07 | access-date=2023-01-17 | archive-date=17 January 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230117162641/https://www.euronews.com/culture/2022/12/07/beyond-rivalry-shared-passion-brings-football-fans-together-in-dubai | url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/sports/2019/1/17/qatar-vs-saudi-arabia-football-blockade-and-piracy-at-asian-cup | title=Qatar vs Saudi Arabia: Football, blockade and piracy at Asian Cup | date=2019-01-17 | access-date=2023-01-17 | archive-date=17 January 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230117162641/https://www.aljazeera.com/sports/2019/1/17/qatar-vs-saudi-arabia-football-blockade-and-piracy-at-asian-cup | url-status=live }}</ref>

==History==
===Early years (1940s–1950s)===
[[Association football|Football]] was brought to [[Qatar]] during a time which coincided with the initial discovery of oil reserves in [[Dukhan]] in 1940.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-14702609|title=Chronological timeline|publisher=bbc.com|date=25 November 2014|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-date=13 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213075832/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-14702609|url-status=live}}</ref> By 1948, teams were created by expatriate oil workers from countries such as [[India]], and various Arabian nations. Among the first documented teams in Qatar were a team formed for the Northern Arab Region, and a team formed near the Al-Khatia area of Dukhan.<ref>{{Cite web |title=حقبة الأربعينيات والخمسينيات - توثيق كرة القدم القطرية |url=https://www.qfl.qa/decades/1/ |access-date=2025-09-27 |website=www.qfl.qa }}{{Dead link|date=January 2026 |bot=InternetArchiveBot }}</ref> The first tournament in the country was the "Ezz Eddin Tournament", held by the Qatar Oil Company in 1951. In the late 1950s, the name was changed to the "Pukett Cup".<ref>{{Cite web |title=Deliver Amazing |url=http://sc.qa/en/qatar/football |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206084225/http://sc.qa/en/qatar/football |archive-date=2015-02-06 |access-date=2025-09-27 |website=Supreme Committee for Delivery & Legacy |language=en}}</ref>

With the growing interest in football, The [[Qatar Football Association]] (QFA) was established in 1960, and the QFA joined [[FIFA]] in 1963.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2022/09/23/has-qatar-been-in-the-world-cup-before-2022-hosts-tournament-record/ | title=Has Qatar been in the World Cup before? 2022 host's tournament record | date=23 September 2022 | access-date=6 November 2022 | archive-date=3 November 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221103084546/https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2022/09/23/has-qatar-been-in-the-world-cup-before-2022-hosts-tournament-record/ | url-status=live }}</ref> Simultaneously during this period, the [[Bahrain Football Association]] were drawing up plans for the establishment of a regional football competition within the [[Cooperation Council for the Arab States of the Gulf|GCC]] and Qatari officials were involved with the collaboration of this proposal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulfcup.com/gulfcup/indexa.php?page=history_a.php|title=Gulf Cup: History|publisher=gulfcup.com|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229232129/http://www.gulfcup.com/gulfcup/indexa.php?page=history_a.php|archive-date=29 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The plans came to fruition and in March of 1970, when the [[Arabian Gulf Cup]] was inaugurated.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gulf-times.com/story/648484/When-Qatar-left-a-mark-at-Arabian-Gulf-Cup | title=When Qatar left a mark at Arabian Gulf Cup | work=Gulf Times | date=24 November 2019 | access-date=6 November 2022 | archive-date=23 March 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220323073212/https://www.gulf-times.com/story/648484/When-Qatar-left-a-mark-at-Arabian-Gulf-Cup | url-status=live }}</ref>

===Rise of Qatari football: 1970s–1980s===
The Qatar national team played its first official match on 27 March 1970 against hosts [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]] in the [[1st Arabian Gulf Cup|1970 Gulf Cup]], losing 1–2 with Mubarak Faraj scoring the sole goal for Qatar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/matcha.php?match_id=36&period=1|title=Match report (Bahrain v Qatar), 1970|publisher=gulfcup.com|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229232001/http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/matcha.php?match_id=36&period=1|archive-date=29 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The newly formed Qatar side gave underwhelming performances in the tournament, coming in last place with a single point, with the highlight of their tournament being a 1–1 draw with rivals [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]] in their final match, and player [[Khaled Ballan]] winning the Best Player of the Tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/tournamenta.php?period=1|title=Final table (1970 Gulf Cup)|publisher=gulfcup.com|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229231907/http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/tournamenta.php?period=1|archive-date=29 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>

In 1972, the next edition of the [[2nd Arabian Gulf Cup|1972 Gulf Cup]], Qatar again finished last place after suffering 3 straight defeats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/tournamenta.php?period=2|title=Final table (1972 Gulf Cup)|publisher=gulfcup.com|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229231944/http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/tournamenta.php?period=2|archive-date=29 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The next tournament in [[3rd Arabian Gulf Cup|1974]] proved to be somewhat of a breakthrough for the Qataris as they achieved their first triumph in international football with a 4–0 victory over [[Oman national football team|Oman]]. The team lost to [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]] in the semi-finals, where they achieved a 3rd place finish in the tournament, after emerging victorious in a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] against the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]], Qatari player [[Mohammed Ghanim (footballer)|Mohammed Ghanim]] won the Best Player of the Tournament award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/matcha.php?match_id=269&period=3|title=Match report (Qatar v UAE), 1974|publisher=gulfcup.com|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229232020/http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/matcha.php?match_id=269&period=3|archive-date=29 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Qatar entered the [[1976 AFC Asian Cup qualification]] for the [[AFC Asian Cup]] which was held in the next year. They were not successful in qualifying, with [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]] and [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]] qualifying. Despite this setback, Qatar went on to finish 3rd place in the [[4th Arabian Gulf Cup|1976 Gulf Cup]] as the host nation the next year, solidifying themselves as one of the best teams in the [[Arab world|Arab region]], with emerging players such as [[Mansour Muftah]], [[Khaled Ballan]], [[Mohammed Ghanim (footballer)|Mohammed Ghanim]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/tournamenta.php?period=4|title=Final table (1976 Gulf Cup)|publisher=gulfcup.com|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229232113/http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/tournamenta.php?period=4|archive-date=29 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>

The national team participated in the [[1978 FIFA World Cup qualification|FIFA World Cup qualifiers]] match for the [[1978 FIFA World Cup]]. Qatar was set to play the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]] on 11 March 1977, but a last-minute with-drawal of the [[Emiratis]] team from the competition merely postponed Qatar's debut until two days later when [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]] were defeated 2–0 in [[Doha]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/01/46/63/42/prelkit2014-2maoverviewlatest.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227040140/http://www.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/01/46/63/42/prelkit2014-2maoverviewlatest.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 December 2014|title=Team preliminary competition facts: AFC|publisher=FIFA|access-date=26 December 2014}}</ref>

===1980s–1990s===
Qatar debuted for their first AFC Asian Cup in the [[1980 AFC Asian Cup]] under Brazilian head coach [[Evaristo de Macedo|Evaristo]]. They had qualified for the tournament after topping a relatively easy group composing of [[Bangladesh national football team|Bangladesh]] and [[Afghanistan national football team|Afghanistan]]. In the main tournament, Qatar was unsuccessful in advancing to the knockout stage, making an early exit from the competition with two defeats, one draw and one win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/80asch.html|title=1980 Asian Nations Cup|website=[[RSSSF]]|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-date=2 September 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230902221846/https://www.rsssf.org/tables/80asch.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

In 1984, Qatar narrowly lost to [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]] in the finals of the [[7th Arabian Gulf Cup|1984 Gulf Cup]], nonetheless they were named runners-up, one of their most impressive achievements until their [[11th Arabian Gulf Cup|1992 Gulf Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/tournamenta.php?period=7|title=Final table (1984 Gulf Cup)|publisher=gulfcup.com|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229231639/http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/tournamenta.php?period=7|archive-date=29 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>

They failed to make it out of the preliminary stages of the [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]] and [[1986 FIFA World Cup]] qualifying rounds. However, the team qualified for both the [[1984 AFC Asian Cup|1984]] and [[1988 AFC Asian Cup|1988]] editions of the Asian Cup. They fell short of qualifying for the semi-finals of the [[1984 AFC Asian Cup|1984]] tournament, with [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]]'s [[Mohaisen Al-Jam'an]]'s 88th-minute goal against [[Kuwait national football team|Kuwait]], ensuring a semi-final position for both teams. They also missed out on a semi-final place in [[1988 AFC Asian Cup|1988]], however, they notably defeated [[Japan national football team|Japan]] by a score of 3–0.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/88asch.html |title=1988 Asian Nations Cup |access-date=26 December 2014 |url-status=live |website=[[RSSSF]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120912132621/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/88asch.html |archive-date=12 September 2012 }}</ref>

===Golden era: 1990s–2000s===
Qatar arguably reached its peak in the 1990s, attaining a [[FIFA]] rating of (53) in August 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=qat/ranking/gender=m/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227033159/http://www.fifa.com/associations/association=qat/ranking/gender=m/|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 December 2013|title=Qatar: FIFA/Coca-Cola World Ranking|publisher=FIFA|access-date=26 December 2014}}</ref> Qatar started off with an emphatic qualifying campaign for the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]], finishing at the top of their group. However they couldn't advance in the tournament, due to finishing below the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]] and [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] in the final round of the qualifiers.

In the [[10th Arabian Gulf Cup|1990 Gulf Cup]], the national team once again finished runners-up as [[Kuwait national football team|Kuwait]] won the final two matches of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/tournamenta.php?period=10|title=Final table (1990 Gulf Cup)|publisher=gulfcup.com|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229231925/http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/tournamenta.php?period=10|archive-date=29 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> 

In 1992, they won the [[11th Arabian Gulf Cup|1992 Gulf Cup]] on home soil for the first time under the leadership of Sebastião Lapola, despite a 1–0 loss against [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]] in their final game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/tournamenta.php?period=11|title=Final table (1992 Gulf Cup)|publisher=gulfcup.com|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617192704/http://www.gulfcup.com/soccer/matches/tournamenta.php?period=11|archive-date=17 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Mubarak Mustafa]], won both the top scorer and man of the tournament awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.raya.com/2023/01/07/%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%b1%d8%a7%d9%8a%d8%a9-%d9%84%d9%88%d9%91%d9%84-%d8%b5%d9%81%d8%ad%d8%a9-%d8%a3%d8%b3%d8%a8%d9%88%d8%b9%d9%8a%d9%91%d8%a9-%d8%aa%d8%b5%d8%af%d8%b1-%d9%83%d9%84-%d8%b3%d8%a8%d8%aa-56/|title=الراية لوّل ….صفحة أسبوعيّة تصدر كل سبت وتستعرض أبرز ما نشرته الراية منذ انطلاق العدد الأوّل منها في 10 مايو 1979|work=جريدة الراية |publisher=Al Raya|language=Arabic|date=7 January 2023|accessdate=10 June 2024}}</ref> They were also named runners-up in the [[13th Arabian Gulf Cup|1996 Gulf Cup]].

Qatar reached the Asian Zone's final qualifying round for the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]. After wins against China and Iran, they played their last match against [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]], where a victory would have earned qualification. However, they lost out as Saudi Arabia won 1–0 to reach the finals.

As [[1998 Arab Cup]] hosts, they finished runners-up to Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesa/arabcup.html|title=1998 Arab Cup|website=[[RSSSF]]|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-date=2 September 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230902222045/https://www.rsssf.org/tablesa/arabcup.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

===2000–2010===
They made it to the quarter-finals of the [[2000 AFC Asian Cup]] despite finishing 3rd in their group, but lost to [[China national football team|China]] in their quarter-final confrontation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/00asch.html|title=2000 Asian Cup|website=[[RSSSF]]|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-date=1 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401085957/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/00asch.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

They reached the final qualifying round again in 2001 but were defeated by [[Bora Milutinovic]]'s China team, who topped the section to progress to their first FIFA World Cup. Frenchman [[Philippe Troussier]] took the manager's job after the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] in [[Korea]] and [[Japan]], but was unsuccessful in both the [[2004 AFC Asian Cup]] and the [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|qualifying campaign]] for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] in [[Germany]].

Troussier was sacked after the World Cup qualifying campaign, and under Bosnian [[Džemaludin Mušović]], the team won the [[Arabian Gulf Cup|Gulf Cup]] in [[17th Arabian Gulf Cup|2004]] and the [[Qatar national under-23 football team|under 23 teams']] [[Football at the 2006 Asian Games|Asian Games]] gold in 2006. Mušović stepped down after Qatar only earned two points from three matches in the [[2007 AFC Asian Cup]].

The job of coaching the team in qualifying for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] fell to Uruguayan head coach [[Jorge Fossati]], who led the team throughout the first and second AFC rounds up to the third round. After leaving them at the top of their group with only two played matches, Fossati had to undergo stomach surgery. Subsequently, the Qatar Football Association ended their cooperation with him in September 2008, as the QFA claimed he needed too long to recover from surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/news/2008/September/24/qatar-fa-sack-jorge-fossati/n134091/|title=Qatar FA sack Jorge Fossati|publisher=soccerway.com|date=24 September 2008|access-date=26 December 2014|archive-date=7 November 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221107103147/https://int.soccerway.com/news/2008/September/24/qatar-fa-sack-jorge-fossati/n134091/|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Bruno Metsu]] was called up for the job, but Qatar failed to qualify after finishing fourth in their qualifying group.

===2010–2020===
[[File:Qatar national football team.jpg|thumb|left|Qatar national team in 2011 during the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] qualifying rounds.]]
Qatar was announced as hosts of the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in December 2010.

In 2011, as hosts of the [[2011 AFC Asian Cup]], they advanced to the quarter-finals. They succumbed to a late 2–3 defeat to eventual champions [[Japan national football team|Japan]] after a goal was scored by [[Masahiko Inoha]] in the 89th minute.

Also, as hosts, they went on to win the [[2013 WAFF Championship]] after defeating [[Jordan national football team|Jordan]] 2–0 in the final. The competition was made up primarily of youth and reserve teams, of which Qatar's was the latter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/world-match-centre/news/newsid/248/709/9/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227041002/http://www.fifa.com/world-match-centre/news/newsid/248/709/9/|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 December 2014|title=Belmadi: Qatar have big ambitions|publisher=FIFA|date=2 December 2014|access-date=26 December 2014}}</ref> [[Djamel Belmadi]], the head coach of the B team, replaced [[Fahad Thani]] as the head coach of the senior team as a result of the team's positive performances. 10 months later, Djamel Belmadi led Qatar to gold in the [[22nd Arabian Gulf Cup|2014 Gulf Cup]]. They advanced from the group stages after three draws, going on to defeat [[Oman national football team|Oman]] 3–1 in the semi-final, and were victorious in the final against [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]], who was playing in front of a home crowd, by a margin of 2–1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/NewsDetails.aspx?storyid=390874|title=Qatar lift Gulf Cup|date=26 November 2014|work=Gulf Daily News|access-date=27 November 2014|archive-date=6 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141206122830/http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/NewsDetails.aspx?storyid=390874|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Despite winning the Gulf Cup and finishing the year 2014 with only one defeat, Qatar showed poor form in the [[2015 AFC Asian Cup]]. Qatar was defeated 1–4 by the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]] in their opener. This was continued with a 0–1 loss to [[Iran national football team|Iran]] and 1–2 to [[Bahrain national football team|Bahrain]]. Qatar was eliminated in the group stages with no points and placed 4th in Group C.

Qatar's campaign in [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|qualifying]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in [[Russia]] was a surprise. Their start in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC second round|second round of FIFA World Cup qualifying]] in the [[Asian Football Confederation|AFC]] was nearly perfect, with seven wins and only one loss. However, their success in the second round didn't follow them to the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC third round|third round]]. Qatar finished bottom of their group, ensuring they would play their first World Cup match on home soil in 2022, the first team to do so since [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in [[1934 FIFA World Cup|1934]].

Qatar continued its poor form in the [[23rd Arabian Gulf Cup|2017 Gulf Cup]], which was hosted by [[Kuwait]]. Qatar opened the tournament with a 4–0 win against [[Yemen national football team|Yemen]], but that was followed by a 1–2 loss to [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]] and an unconvincing 1–1 draw to Bahrain. Qatar took third place in Group B with four points and was eliminated in the group stage of the competition, which was considered an upsetting of the tournament, especially after winning the 2014 edition.

