However, Qatar had an excellent campaign at the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup]]. Their opener saw them defeat [[Lebanon national football team|Lebanon]] 2–0. This was followed by a 6–0 thrashing of [[North Korea national football team|North Korea]] and a 2–0 win against three-time champions Saudi Arabia, which sealed the team getting first place in the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup Group E|group]]. They had a 1–0 win against Iraq in the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup knockout stage#Qatar vs Iraq|Round of 16]] and a late win against defending runners-up [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] in the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup knockout stage#South Korea vs Qatar|quarter-finals]], seeing them through to the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup knockout stage#Qatar vs United Arab Emirates|semi-finals]] for the first time ever, where they defeated the hosts United Arab Emirates 4–0 to set up a final against 4-time winners Japan. Qatar ended up winning the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup Final|final]] 3–1 over Japan, marking their first-ever major tournament title in their history, and capping off one of the most improbable Asian Cup runs in the tournament's history, especially since they conceded only one goal in all their games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/feb/01/qatar-stun-japan-with-3-1-win-to-be-crowned-asian-cup-champions|title=Qatar stun Japan with 3–1 win to be crowned Asian Cup champions|date=1 February 2019|website=theguardian.com|publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited|access-date=5 February 2019|archive-date=7 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507081628/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/feb/01/qatar-stun-japan-with-3-1-win-to-be-crowned-asian-cup-champions|url-status=live}}</ref>	 
{{clear|left}}

Qatar was invited to the [[2019 Copa América]]. They were placed in [[2019 Copa América Group B|Group B]] with [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]], [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] and [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]]. Their first game was against Paraguay where they came back from a 2–0 deficit to tie it 2–2, but this marked the first time Qatar suffered more than one goal in any major competition since winning the Asian Cup in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/06/16/qatar-shake-up-copa-with-thrilling-comeback-against-paraguay |title=Qatar shake up Copa with thrilling comeback against Paraguay |website=euronews.com |publisher=Euronews |date=16 June 2019 |access-date=17 June 2019 |archive-date=24 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201024234520/https://www.euronews.com/2019/06/16/qatar-shake-up-copa-with-thrilling-comeback-against-paraguay |url-status=live }}</ref> It was followed by a 0–1 loss to Colombia, ending the team's undefeated streak in any major competition to eight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=535891|title=Colombia in Copa quarters with win over Qatar|website=espn.com|publisher=ESPN|date=19 June 2019|access-date=9 July 2019|archive-date=20 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620202631/https://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=535891|url-status=live}}</ref> A 0–2 loss to Argentina meant Qatar took the last place in Group B with a single point and was eliminated in the group stage of the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jun/23/qatar-argentina--copa-america-match-report|title=Sergio Agüero guides Argentina past Qatar to reach Copa América last eight|website=theguardian.com|publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited|date=23 June 2019|access-date=9 July 2019|archive-date=26 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201126140807/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jun/23/qatar-argentina--copa-america-match-report|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Preparation for the FIFA World Cup as host: 2020–present ===
Despite Qatar having automatic qualification for the 2022 World Cup as hosts, they had to play the AFC qualifiers in the second round as part of it also acting as qualification for the [[2023 AFC Asian Cup]] and won 7 of 8 games, conceding only one goal. Qatar was invited for the first time to the [[2021 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]. They played in [[2021 CONCACAF Gold Cup|Group D]] with [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]], [[Panama national football team|Panama]] and [[Grenada national football team|Grenada]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.the-afc.com/en/more/news/qatar_in_group_d_of_2021_concacaf_gold_cup.html | title=Qatar in Group D of 2021 Concacaf Gold Cup | date=2020-09-29 | access-date=2022-12-29 | archive-date=29 December 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221229080201/https://www.the-afc.com/en/more/news/qatar_in_group_d_of_2021_concacaf_gold_cup.html | url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2020, [[UEFA]] invited Qatar to play [[Exhibition game|friendlies]] against the teams in [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group A|Group A of the 2022 World Cup qualifying group]] – [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]], [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]], [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] and [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]] – as five teams in one group means one team will not be playing on any given match day. These friendlies did not count in the qualifying group standings. Qatar played their "home" matches in Europe in order to allow short travel times for their opponents.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/news/0264-11103d6ec600-5258c3966355-1000/ |title=Group A matches with Qatar |work=UEFA |date=11 December 2020 |access-date=12 December 2020 |archive-date=31 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201231182744/https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/news/0264-11103d6ec600-5258c3966355-1000/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://editorial.uefa.com/resources/0264-110ad9b5b487-e3521001b47e-1000/group_a_-_fixtures_list_with_qatar.pdf |title=World Cup Qualifying Calendar – Group A with Qatar |work=UEFA |date=8 December 2020 |access-date=8 December 2020 |archive-date=18 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210118003759/https://editorial.uefa.com/resources/0264-110ad9b5b487-e3521001b47e-1000/group_a_-_fixtures_list_with_qatar.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>
[[File:QAT-ECU 2022-11-20.svg|thumb|Qatar opening match starting line-up against Ecuador at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]]. ]]
In the [[2021 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], Qatar claimed 7 points in [[2021 CONCACAF Gold Cup|Group D]]. Their debut was against [[Panama national football team|Panama]] with a 3–3 draw, ensuring them their first point. This was followed by a 4–0 victory over [[Grenada national football team|Grenada]] and a 2–0 win over [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]] ensuring a quarter-final place where they would face [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]], ultimately securing a semi-final place against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] with a 3–2 win. However, against the hosts with its squad made up of the majority of [[Major League Soccer|MLS]] players, Qatar failed to find the way to the net, in spite of having a penalty in the 60th minute, ultimately conceding a late goal from [[Gyasi Zardes]] to end Qatar's campaign with a 1–0 loss. In the [[2021 FIFA Arab Cup]], Qatar won all of its group-stage matches and faced [[United Arab Emirates national football team|UAE]], winning 5–0. They lost 2–1 in the semi-final against [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/arabcup/arabcup2021/match-center/400175832 | title=FIFA Arab Cup • 15 Dec 2021 • 11:00 • Al Thumama Stadium | date=2021-12-15 | access-date=2022-12-28 | archive-date=29 December 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221229075922/https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/arabcup/arabcup2021/match-center/400175832 | url-status=live }}</ref> eventually placing 3rd.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/12/18/qatar-beats-egypt-to-join-fifa-2021-arab-cup-podium | title=Qatar beats Egypt to clinch third place at FIFA Arab Cup 2021 | date=2021-12-18 | access-date=2022-12-28 | archive-date=27 May 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230527030941/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/12/18/qatar-beats-egypt-to-join-fifa-2021-arab-cup-podium | url-status=live }}</ref>

Despite the very successful performance of Qatar in various major tournaments, the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] held at home proved to be a nightmare for the Qataris. Being automatically drawn into the [[2022 FIFA World Cup Group A|Group A]] as hosts, Qatar started with a 0–2 loss to [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]] in the opening match, conceding two goals in the first half from [[Enner Valencia]], making Qatar the first host country to lose their opening game.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Qatar 0-2 Ecuador: Enner Valencia at the double as hosts lose World Cup opener for first time |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12098/12751714/qatar-0-2-ecuador-enner-valencia-at-the-double-as-hosts-lose-world-cup-opener-for-first-time |access-date=2022-12-05 |website=Sky Sports |language=en |archive-date=5 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221205194915/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12098/12751714/qatar-0-2-ecuador-enner-valencia-at-the-double-as-hosts-lose-world-cup-opener-for-first-time |url-status=live }}</ref> The situation did not improve for the Qataris in their second meeting with Senegal, when the Africans beat the Qataris 3–1 to condemn the hosts to an early World Cup exit, becoming the second host country after [[South Africa national soccer team|South Africa]], the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] hosts, to have such an unwanted record (although they were eliminated only on inferior goal differences to [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] after three matches); they became the first host team to be eliminated after two group games and guaranteed to be the worst-host ever, although Ghanaian-born [[Mohammed Muntari]] became Qatar's first World Cup scorer in this game.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-11-25 |title=Qatar 1-3 Senegal: World Cup hosts eliminated from tournament in record time despite scoring historic goal in Group A |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/world-cup/2022/fifa-world-cup-2022-in-qatar-live-qatar-v-senegal-updates_sto9237968/story.shtml |access-date=2024-02-28 |website=Eurosport |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Archer |first=Kyle |date=2022-11-26 |title=Worst World Cup host nations as Qatar become first team eliminated in 2022 |url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2022/11/26/worst-world-cup-host-nations-with-qatar-the-first-team-eliminated-in-2022/ |access-date=2024-02-28 |website=HITC |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Brown |first=Luke |title=Qatar lose again — but has a host nation ever been knocked out in the World Cup group stage? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3934896/2022/11/25/qatar-hosts-world-cup-group-qualifying/ |access-date=2024-02-28 |website=The Athletic |date=29 November 2022 |language=en}}</ref> With Qatar's elimination confirmed, the hosts then fell to the Netherlands 0–2, making an unwanted record as the first hosts to score the fewest goals (1), the first to lose all three group games, and the lowest-ranked team in the tournament (ranked 32nd).<ref>{{Cite web |last=Furniss |first=Matt |date=2022-11-29 |title=Netherlands 2-0 Qatar: Dutch Delight |url=https://theanalyst.com/2022/11/netherlands-2-0-qatar-world-cup-stats/ |access-date=2024-02-28 |website=The Analyst |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-11-29 |title=Qatar performance is worst ever by a World Cup host nation |url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20221129-qatar-performance-is-worst-ever-by-a-world-cup-host-nation |access-date=2024-02-28 |website=France 24 |language=en}}</ref>

14 months later, they would redeem themselves at the [[2023 AFC Asian Cup]], also held at home. The Maroons defeated [[Lebanon national football team|Lebanon]] 3–0 to start off their campaign, and they entered the round of 16 as group winners following 2 other successes, all without conceding a goal. They had to overcome [[Palestine national football team|Palestine]] (2–1) and then [[Uzbekistan national football team|Uzbekistan]] in the next round (1–1 a.e.t., 3 p.s.o. to 2) to reach the last four, but without convincing. After defeating [[Iran]] narrowly in a 3–2 dramatic semifinal match, they would face off against [[Jordan]] in the final, where a penalty hat-trick by [[Akram Afif]] helped Qatar defeat [[Jordan national football team|Jordan]] 3–1 to clinch their second successive [[AFC Asian Cup]], becoming the first team since [[Japan national football team|Japan]] to successfully defend their title.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-02-10 |title=Afif stakes claim as one of Asian Cup's greatest as Qatar win back-to-back titles |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/39498805/akram-afif-stakes-claim-asian-cup-greatest-qatar-win-back-back-titles |access-date=2024-02-28 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |agency=Reuters |date=2024-02-10 |title=Akram Afif's hat-trick of penalties secures Asian Cup glory for Qatar |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2024/feb/10/qatar-jordan-asian-cup-final-match-report |access-date=2024-02-28 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-02-10 |title=Qatar win back-to-back AFC Asian Cup championships behind three penalties from magic man Akram Afif |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/qatar-win-back-to-back-afc-asian-cup-championships-behind-three-penalties-from-magic-man-akram-afif/ |access-date=2024-02-28 |website=CBSSports.com |language=en}}</ref>

On 14 October 2025, Qatar secured qualification for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]] after defeating the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]] 2–1 at the [[Jassim bin Hamad Stadium]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]]. The result marked their first-ever qualification for a World Cup through the standard AFC qualification process, having previously participated in [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]] as hosts.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Qatar reach World Cup through qualification for first time, beating UAE |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/sports/2025/10/14/qatar-reach-world-cup-through-qualification-for-first-time-beating-uae |access-date=2025-10-15 |website=Al Jazeera |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Qatar 2 - 1 United Arab Emirates |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/match-centre/match/520/288263/288279/400020391 |access-date=2025-10-15 |website=www.fifa.com}}</ref>

