===Naturalised players===
While it is reasonably common for footballers to represent national teams other than their birth nations,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/magazine/2018/07/world-cup-fifa-soccer-players-national-teams-foreign-born/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703154203/https://www.nationalgeographic.com/magazine/2018/07/world-cup-fifa-soccer-players-national-teams-foreign-born/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 July 2018 |title=See Which World Cup Teams Have the Most Foreign-Born Players |website=[[National Geographic]] |date=July 2018 |access-date=1 July 2019 |first=Riley |last=Champine}}</ref> the nature and extent of the practice for the Qatari team have been the subject of scrutiny and criticism at various points during the 21st century. In the early 1970s, shortly after the formation of the national team, the [[Qatar Football Association|QFA]] revealed that it had naturalized its first players in a February 1976 telegram sent to FIFA: Ezzuldin Osman of Sudan, Hassan Mukhtar of Egypt and Ryad Murad of Lebanon. This practice of naturalizing Arabic-speaking foreigners to compete for the national team continued throughout the 20th century, albeit at a relatively slow rate.<ref>{{cite thesis|url=https://fis.dshs-koeln.de/portal/files/3998204/Rolim_Silva_PHD_FULL_DOC.pdf|title=The Formation of an Olympic Nation in the Persian Gulf: sociocultural history of the sport in Qatar, 1948-1984|year=2019|author=Luís Henrique Rolim Silva|publisher=Deutsche Sporthochschule Köln|pages=272–273|access-date=16 June 2023|archive-date=15 December 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221215083615/https://fis.dshs-koeln.de/portal/files/3998204/Rolim_Silva_PHD_FULL_DOC.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2004, FIFA cited the intention of three Brazilian players – [[Aílton (footballer, born 1973)|Aílton]], [[Dedé (footballer, born 1978)|Dedé]] and [[Leandro de Deus Santos|Leandro]] – to play for the Qatar national team as the immediate trigger to their decision to tighten eligibility rules to ensure players have ties to the country they represent.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/who-we-are/news/players-seeking-naturalisation-with-clear-connection-country-ineligibl-91082 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201024011803/https://www.fifa.com/who-we-are/news/players-seeking-naturalisation-with-clear-connection-country-ineligibl-91082 |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 October 2020 |title=Players seeking naturalisation with no clear connection to country ineligible to represent national teams |website=[[FIFA]] |date=17 March 2004 |access-date=21 September 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/africa/3523266.stm |title=Fifa rules on eligibility |website=[[BBC Sport]] |date=18 March 2004 |access-date=1 July 2019 |archive-date=23 July 2004 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040723224447/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/3523266.stm |url-status=live }}</ref>

While Qatari authorities described it as a humanitarian effort and a way to provide competition for native Qatari players, critics claimed that it was merely another exploitative way of acquiring naturalized players,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/is-this-the-academy-of-dreams-or-exploitation-1.1906302 |title=Is this the academy of dreams or exploitation? |newspaper=[[The Irish Times]] |date=23 August 2014 |access-date=1 July 2019 |first1=Steve |last1=Eder |first2=Christopher |last2=Harress |first3=Sam |last3=Borden |first4=Jack |last4=Williams |archive-date=12 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200812182011/https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/is-this-the-academy-of-dreams-or-exploitation-1.1906302 |url-status=live }}</ref> with ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' linking it to human rights abuses and the [[kafala system]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/does-qatars-football-policy-put-players-at-risk-of-exploitation/ |title=Does Qatar's Football Policy Put Players at Risk of Exploitation? |website=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] |date=9 January 2017 |access-date=1 July 2019 |first=Hayden |last=Vernon |archive-date=1 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701234408/https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/z4ayz5/does-qatars-football-policy-put-players-at-risk-of-exploitation |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[International Labour Organization]] (ILO) and Qatar announced the removal of the Kafala on 12 December 2016; the law came into effect in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Qatar's human-rights reversal |url=https://www.ips-journal.eu/work-and-digitalisation/qatars-human-rights-reversal-5977/ |access-date=26 September 2022 |website=IPS |date=8 June 2022 |language=en-GB |archive-date=26 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220926121610/https://www.ips-journal.eu/work-and-digitalisation/qatars-human-rights-reversal-5977/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The reform took place between UN's International labor organization and the state of Qatar and was proven to be the part of many said assurances that nation has claimed for the 2022 World Cup. Though claimed by independent bodies of Qatar foundering to achieve the same, both sides had agreed to revise previous acts that had been taken. To make this all possible, the hosting country declared to pay compensation for the deaths of its migrant workers on 12 August 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 August 2022 |title=FIFA/Qatar: Commit to Compensate Abused Migrant Workers |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2022/08/12/fifa/qatar-commit-compensate-abused-migrant-workers |access-date=26 September 2022 |website=Human Rights Watch |language=en |archive-date=26 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220926121607/https://www.hrw.org/news/2022/08/12/fifa/qatar-commit-compensate-abused-migrant-workers |url-status=live }}</ref>

Job changes between September 2020 and March 2022, the establishment of a nondiscriminatory wage system for all workers in March 2021, and workers' funds and insurance policies in the workplace are all data that showcased the functioning of the state for its workers.<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 May 2021 |title=Overview of Qatar's labor reforms |url=https://www.ilo.org/beirut/countries/qatar/WCMS_760466/lang--en/index.htm |website=International Labor Organization |access-date=26 September 2022 |archive-date=26 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220926121608/https://www.ilo.org/beirut/countries/qatar/WCMS_760466/lang--en/index.htm |url-status=live }}</ref>

In the 2015 friendly against [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]], six of the eleven players in the starting team were born outside of Qatar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32147203 |title=How will Qatar build a good team for the 2022 World Cup? |website=[[BBC Sport]] |date=8 April 2015 |access-date=1 July 2019 |first=Alex |last=South |archive-date=2 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702080034/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32147203 |url-status=live }}</ref> Then-president of FIFA, [[Sepp Blatter]], warned Qatar that FIFA would monitor their player selection to ensure that they were not relying too heavily on naturalised players. He made comparisons to the [[Qatar men's national handball team]], referring to the team's selection for the [[2015 World Men's Handball Championship]] as an "absurdity".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/fifa-world-cup/story/2285181/fifa-chief-sepp-blatter-warns-qatar-over-imported-players-for-2022-world-cup?src=com |title=FIFA chief Sepp Blatter warns Qatar over imported players for 2022 |website=[[ESPN]] |date=6 February 2015 |access-date=1 July 2019 |archive-date=2 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702103530/https://www.espn.co.uk/football/fifa-world-cup/story/2285181/fifa-chief-sepp-blatter-warns-qatar-over-imported-players-for-2022-world-cup%3Fsrc%3Dcom |url-status=live }}</ref> The following year, naturalized players formed the backbone of the team and were sufficiently integral that head coach [[Jorge Fossati]] threatened to resign if they were removed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-worldcup-qatar/qatar-soccer-coach-threatens-to-resign-if-naturalised-players-excluded-idUKKBN13I0UA |title=Qatar soccer coach threatens to resign if naturalised players excluded |website=[[Reuters]] |date=23 November 2016 |access-date=1 July 2019 |first=Tom |last=Finn |archive-date=1 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701234407/https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-worldcup-qatar/qatar-soccer-coach-threatens-to-resign-if-naturalised-players-excluded-idUKKBN13I0UA |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dohastadiumplusqatar.com/contentpage.aspx?article=End-of-naturalisation |title=End of naturalisation? |website=Doha Stadium Plus |date=23 November 2016 |access-date=1 July 2019 |archive-date=1 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191201004140/http://www.dohastadiumplusqatar.com/contentpage.aspx?article=End-of-naturalisation |url-status=dead }}</ref>

The reliance on naturalised players has subsequently reduced, with only two members of the squad that beat [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] in a 2018 friendly being born outside Qatar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/fifa-world-cup/4/blog/post/3700843/qatars-unknown-players-may-not-be-the-2022-world-cup-flops-theyre-expected-to-be |title=Qatar's mystery men may not be the 2022 World Cup flops they're expected to be |website=[[ESPN]] |date=15 November 2018 |access-date=1 July 2019 |first=Mark |last=Ogden |archive-date=1 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701234406/https://www.espn.com/soccer/fifa-world-cup/4/blog/post/3700843/qatars-unknown-players-may-not-be-the-2022-world-cup-flops-theyre-expected-to-be |url-status=live }}</ref> However, at the [[2019 AFC Asian Cup|2019 Asian Cup]], amidst [[Qatar–United Arab Emirates relations|diplomatic tensions between the two countries]], the [[United Arab Emirates Football Association]] lodged a formal complaint against Qatar, alleging that [[Almoez Ali]] and [[Bassam Al-Rawi]] were not eligible to play for them.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/31/sports/soccer/qatar-uae-asian-cup.html |title=U.A.E. Accuses Qatar of Fielding Ineligible Players at Asian Cup |website=[[New York Times]] |date=31 January 2019 |access-date=1 July 2019 |first=Tariq |last=Panja |archive-date=1 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201104735/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/31/sports/soccer/qatar-uae-asian-cup.html |url-status=live }}</ref> These complaints were dismissed by the AFC.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.the-afc.com/news/afcsection/uae-fa-protest-dismissed |title=UAE FA protest dismissed |website=The-AFC.com |publisher=[[Asian Football Confederation]] |date=1 February 2019 |access-date=1 July 2019 |archive-date=7 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201107224033/https://www.the-afc.com/news/afcsection/uae-fa-protest-dismissed |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-asiancup-final/uae-protest-at-eligibility-of-qataris-dismissed-on-day-of-final-idUKKCN1PQ4JC|title=UAE protest at eligibility of Qataris dismissed on day of final|first1=Nick|last1=Mulvenney|first2=Alexander|last2=Cornwell|work=Reuters|date=1 February 2019|access-date=1 July 2019|archive-date=4 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201004024616/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-asiancup-final/uae-protest-at-eligibility-of-qataris-dismissed-on-day-of-final-idUKKCN1PQ4JC|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Of the 26 players called up to the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], 10 players were born outside of Qatar.<ref name=":0">{{Cite tweet |user=QFA_EN |number=1591124871764791297 |date=11 November 2022 |title=Our national team squad for the #2022WorldCup}}</ref>

